Conventional Approach:

A traditional focus has been on surveying the seafloor using sonar equipment that captures images and sounds from depths up to several hundred meters. This technique tends to be slow due to its reliance on technology and often leads to a high cost, as well as a lack of immediate access in certain areas.

Advantages:
- Faster time-to-reach data; 
- Can conduct detailed surveys without physical disturbance;
- Precise mapping of seafloor features;

Limitations:
- Not always capturing the full range of marine archaeological contexts and phenomena;
- Lack of flexibility to address specific questions,
- May not be suitable for less accessible areas.

Emerging Approach:

With advancements in advanced technology, there has been a shift towards more specialized approaches like underwater robotic systems (ULR), remotely operated vehicles (ROVs) or autonomous robots. These technologies allow collecting large volumes of data and conducting comprehensive analyses over extended periods of time.

Advantages:
- Increased flexibility;
- Can collect detailed imagery of the seafloor,
- Often have lower costs due to increased efficiency,
- Better coverage of marine archaeological studies;

Limitations:
- Require specialized training and equipment, leading to a higher cost;
- May not capture all relevant information; 
- Requires more frequent field work in inaccessible areas. 

So while both approaches are valuable tools for conducting marine archaeology, the emerging approach offers flexibility, efficiency, detailed imagery coverage but also comes with additional costs and limitations that conventional methods do not necessarily have.

